The Trump administration and the economy
New York—Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is the president of the United States.
The world has endured the unfiltered tweets and public remarks of the globally most powerful person for two years, and the obvious question is: what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, investors have, until now, artificially kept Trump pegged as a rainmaker who talks the talk but doesn't walk the walk.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies that benefit the business sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that in the end, "the adults in the room" will constrain Trump and ensure that government policies stay within bounds.
Such assumptions were more or less borne out during Trump’s first year in office, a period when growth and expectations for corporate profits — fueled by impending tax cuts and deregulation — propelled the stock market to impressive heights.
In 2017, the American stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, things took a turn for the worse, especially in the last few months.
Despite company profits increasing by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), U.S. stocks oscillated for much of the year and are now plunging sharply.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (down 10% from recent highs), and tech stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Despite the increased volatility in financial markets reflecting concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is attributable to Trump.
At the outset of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and brought the already near-full-employment economy to a peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first risk-off tide of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies in the market have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
The recent moves by the United States towards China seem to be preparing for a full-scale trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump’s other policies could have a stagflationary effect (weak growth and rising inflation).
After all, Trump was preparing to restrict foreign direct investment and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will drag on the growth of labor supply in an increasingly severe situation of an aging workforce and skill mismatches.
Moreover, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan that would stimulate private-sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other platforms, Trump constantly criticized businesses for their hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, particularly those of tech companies, which already face widespread opposition and increasing competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening pushed up both short-term and long-term interest rates, reinforcing the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies encountered capital outflows and an increase in the value of their dollar-denominated debt.
Then, emerging economies that are heavily dependent on exports have suffered from the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy created volatility.
The restart of U.S. sanctions on Iran pushed up oil prices, which subsequently dropped after the U.S. government revoked exemptions and threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production.
Despite American consumers benefiting from low oil prices, the stock prices of American energy companies are struggling.
In addition, excessive volatility in oil prices is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it now appears that almost all of last year’s tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may slow down quickly, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent dramatic plunge of both the US and global stock markets is Trump himself, in terms of his statements and actions.
Worse than the突出 risk of an all-out trade war with China erupting (despite his recent truce with Chinese President Xi Jinping), Trump’s public criticism of the Federal Reserve is even worse. His attacks began in the spring of 2018 when US economic growth was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became jumpy this month when the Fed raised interest rates correctly but signaled that it would hike rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Fed's relatively hawkish stance is a response to Trump's criticisms of it.
Facing hostile tweets from President Donald Trump, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down the federal government partially.
This has put the market into near panic mode, and with the government shutdown, reports quickly emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell – which could turn a correction into a full-blown crash.
Before the Christmas holiday period, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the markets.
He declared that Trump had no plans to fire Powell, the US fiscal situation was in good shape, which actually highlights the question of whether things really are as good as they seem.
And personnel changes within the government, which may not necessarily affect economic decisions, have recently also caused market concern.
John Kelly, the White House chief of staff, and James Mattis, the secretary of defense, are set to leave their positions, leaving no sound minds in Trump’s cabinet.
The rest will be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks following Trump’s lead.
At present, the possibility of a comprehensive geoeconomic conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new cold war is likely to lead to de-globalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the tech industry will bear the brunt of this, as recent cases with ZTE and Huawei serve as clear evidence.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during Europe's economic and political instability.
The investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign ties to Russia by Special Counsel Robert Mueller is like the sword of Damocles hanging over the presidency of President Trump.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic films, he is unable to extricate himself from a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market sees the danger, with the risk of financial crisis and global recession rising steadily.
